n their place he proposes a covenant concept of state, community, and family assurances to derive from our common provision of a civic endowment that we undertake to sustain now and for future generations of Canadians.O'Neill argues that if Canada is to survive as a national community capable of responding to the global market, we must reaffirm the civic foundations of the state. If we fail to do this, we will not have a leaner society, only a meaner one. This society will be hostile to capitalism and socialism alike. If we can rededicate the Canadian commons to the well-being of the civic person, Canada will contribute a model of survival and governance among the nations of the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChild welfarexCanada. 0aChild welfarezCanada. 0aChild welfare. 0aChildrenxGovernment policyxCanada. 0aChildrenxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aChildrenxGovernment policy. 0aEnfantsxPolitique gouvernementalexCanada. 0aEnfantsxPolitique gouvernementale. 0aEnfantsxProtection, assistance, etcxCanada. 0aEnfantsxProtection, assistance, etc. 0aFamily policyxCanada. 0aFamily policyzCanada. 0aFamily policy. 0aPolitique familialexCanadaxCanadaxKanada. 0aPolitique familiale. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148758585340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487585853423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487585853.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEB